SIMPLE: ablation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ablation
<hw>Ab*la"tion</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>ablatio</ets>, fr. <ets>ablatus</ets> p. p. of <ets>auferre</ets>
to carry away; <ets>ab</ets> + <ets>latus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>ferre</ets> carry: cf. F. <ets>ablation</ets>. See
<er>Tolerate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A carrying or taking away;
removal.</def> <rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Extirpation.</def>
<rj><au>Dunglison.</au></rj> <ver>AS</ver>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Removing or destroying of a body
tissue, especially by a surgical procedure.</def> <au>Dorland.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>AS</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Geol.)</fld> <def>Wearing away; superficial waste,
as of glacial ice or snow.</def> <rj><au>Tyndall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Aerospace)</fld> <def>Wearing away of the outer
layers of a protective shield or surface by the heat and aerodynamic
forces caused by flying through the atmosphere at hypersonic speed, as
during reentry from space; <as>as, <ex>ablation</ex> of the heat shield
during reentry</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ablatitious</ent>⟦br⟧
